cs.NI, cs.IT, cs.MM, cs.CR, cs.SY 

This paper deals with cross-layer optimization for routing information in wireless body-to-body networks, which involves aspects of networking (cs.NI), information theory (cs.IT), multimedia (cs.MM), cryptography and security (cs.CR), and systems and control (cs.SY). The paper uses experimental measurements to analyze and compare different routing protocols, which is a common approach in the networking community (cs.NI). The paper also discusses the distribution of channel gains, which is a topic of interest in information theory (cs.IT). The use of wireless body-to-body networks for mixed-activities involves multimedia data, such as audio and video, which falls under the category of multimedia (cs.MM). The paper also discusses the impact of routing protocols on energy consumption and delay, which are important considerations in systems and control (cs.SY). Finally, the paper discusses the impact of routing protocols on security and reliability, which are topics of interest in cryptography and security (cs.CR).
